Below is one way to modify your renderBooksTable() function so that the Update and Delete “buttons” are implemented as hyperlinks (with href="#" and onclick events) while still looking like buttons. In this example, we create anchor elements styled to appear as buttons. They call updateBook() or deleteBook() with the book’s Bid when clicked and then prevent the default link behavior.

```js
function renderBooksTable() {
    // Select the table body of the booksTable
    const tbody = document.querySelector('#booksTable tbody');

    // Clear any existing rows
    tbody.innerHTML = '';

    // Loop through each book in the books array
    books.forEach((book, index) => {
        // Create a new table row
        const row = document.createElement('tr');

        // Create and append cells for Bid, Bname, Bpd, Bcountry, and Bprice
        const cellBid = document.createElement('td');
        cellBid.textContent = book.Bid;
        row.appendChild(cellBid);

        const cellBname = document.createElement('td');
        cellBname.textContent = book.Bname;
        row.appendChild(cellBname);

        const cellBpd = document.createElement('td');
        cellBpd.textContent = book.Bpd;
        row.appendChild(cellBpd);

        const cellBcountry = document.createElement('td');
        cellBcountry.textContent = book.Bcountry;
        row.appendChild(cellBcountry);

        const cellBprice = document.createElement('td');
        // Format the price to two decimal places
        cellBprice.textContent = book.Bprice.toFixed(2);
        row.appendChild(cellBprice);

        // Create the Action cell with Update and Delete buttons
        const cellAction = document.createElement('td');

        // Update button as a hyperlink styled like a button
        const updateButton = document.createElement('a');
        updateButton.href = "#";
        updateButton.onclick = function() {
            updateBook(book.Bid);
            return false; // Prevent default link behavior
        };
        updateButton.textContent = 'Update';
        // Optional styling to look like a button
        updateButton.style.padding = "4px 8px";
        updateButton.style.border = "1px solid #ccc";
        updateButton.style.backgroundColor = "#eee";
        updateButton.style.textDecoration = "none";
        updateButton.style.cursor = "pointer";
        cellAction.appendChild(updateButton);

        // Add a space between the buttons
        cellAction.appendChild(document.createTextNode(' '));

        // Delete button as a hyperlink styled like a button
        const deleteButton = document.createElement('a');
        deleteButton.href = "#";
        deleteButton.onclick = function() {
            deleteBook(book.Bid);
            return false; // Prevent default link behavior
        };
        deleteButton.textContent = 'Delete';
        // Optional styling to look like a button
        deleteButton.style.padding = "4px 8px";
        deleteButton.style.border = "1px solid #ccc";
        deleteButton.style.backgroundColor = "#eee";
        deleteButton.style.textDecoration = "none";
        deleteButton.style.cursor = "pointer";
        cellAction.appendChild(deleteButton);

        row.appendChild(cellAction);

        // Append the row to the table body
        tbody.appendChild(row);
    });
}
```

### Explanation

- **Hyperlink functionality:**  
  Instead of using plain `<button>` elements (which do not support an href attribute), we create `<a>` elements. Each anchor is given `href="#"` to mimic hyperlink behavior.

- **Onclick events:**  
  The `onclick` attributes for the Update and Delete elements call `updateBook(book.Bid)` and `deleteBook(book.Bid)`, respectively. Returning `false` prevents the default action of the link.

- **Styling as buttons:**  
  The inline styles (padding, border, background color, etc.) are added to give the anchors the look and feel of buttons. You can adjust or move these styles to a CSS file as needed.

- **Action on the Create/Update Book table data:**  
  When updateBook() is called, you can design that function to retrieve the current form values from your Create/Update Book table (or prefill the form with the selected row’s data). Similarly, deleteBook() should act on the corresponding record.

This enhancement meets your requirements by giving the Update and Delete elements hyperlink functionality while retaining their “button” appearance.

